\section{Introduction}
\label{section1}

If the renormalization group flow of a quantum field theory has a stable conformal fixed point, and the fixed point preserves more symmetries(besides conformal symmetry itself) than the original theory, then these extra symmetries will emerge as a result of renormalization group flow. Emergent supersymmetry has been found in different contexts, for example, in topological superconductors\cite{2014Sci...344..280G}, and in a class of models in 1+1 dimensions \cite{Huijse:2014ata}. In this paper, we show that supersymmetry emerges in a four dimensional renormalizable quantum field theory: a deformed $\mathcal{N}=4$ SYM in the planar limit.

The most general superconformal deformation of $\mathcal{N}=4$ SYM is the Leigh-Strassler deformation\cite{Leigh:1995ep}. As a conformal field theory, the Leigh-Strassler deformation is a fixed line in the space of more general deformations. However, it is technically difficult to determine whether this fixed line is stable or not, given the huge number of parameters in the Yukawa and quartic scalar couplings. 

We shall start in Section \ref{section2} by introducing the renormalization potentials. We show that the renormalization group flow of Yukawa and quartic scalar couplings are characterized by two scalar quantities, which will be named as renormalization potentials of Yukawa and quartic couplings, respectively. The renormalization group flow is given by the gradient of renormalization potentials. Renormalization potentials are very helpful in the study of renormalization group flows, especially in theories with large number of parameters.

With the help of renormalization potentials we study the flow of Yukawa couplings in Section \ref{section3}, and prove that at low energies the Yukawa couplings always flow to conformal fixed points. In Section \ref{section4}, in order to prove that the Leigh-Strassler theory is locally the only conformal field theory, we present a method of counting physical parameters by a classification of protected operators. Then in Section \ref{section5} we study the renormalization group flow around the Leigh-Strassler deformation, and show that although the Leigh-Strassler theory is a saddle point of generic deformations, it becomes stable if only a subspace of (but still non-supersymmetric) deformations are turned on.

